# Elm Syntax Conventions

This rule defines standard import patterns and syntax conventions for using `mdgriffith/elm-ui` Element module and `elm/html`.

## Element Module Imports

When using `elm-ui`, follow these import patterns:

### When Using Only elm-ui Modules

If your module **only** uses elm-ui modules (no `Html` or `Html.Attributes`), you can use aliases:

```elm
import Element exposing (Element)
import Element.Background as Background
import Element.Font as Font
import Element.Input as Input
```

**Usage with aliases:**

```elm
Element.el
    [ Background.color (Element.rgb255 150 150 250)
    , Font.size 16
    ]
    (Element.text "Hello")
```

### When Mixing elm-ui with Html

If your module uses **both** elm-ui modules **and** `Html`/`Html.Attributes`, use fully qualified names without aliases to avoid confusion:

```elm
import Element exposing (Element)
import Element.Background
import Element.Font
import Html exposing (Html)
import Html.Attributes as Attr
```

**Usage with fully qualified names:**

```elm
Element.el
    [ Element.Background.color (Element.rgb255 150 150 250)
    , Element.Font.size 16
    ]
    (Element.text "Hello")
```

**Guidelines:**

-   Use `import Element exposing (Element)` to expose only the Element type
-   **Only elm-ui**: Aliases are fine (`import Element.Background as Background`)
-   **Mixed with Html**: Use fully qualified names without aliases (`import Element.Background`)
-   This prevents confusion between `Element.Font.color` and `Html.Attributes.style`

### Additional Common Imports

You may also need:

```elm
import Element.Font
import Element.Input
```

### Code Example: Mixed elm-ui and Html

```elm
import Element exposing (Element)
import Element.Background
import Html exposing (Html)
import Html.Attributes as Attr

main : Html msg
main =
    Element.layout []
        -- layout converts from Element to Html
        box

box : Element a
box =
    Element.el
        [ Element.centerX -- these two centers the div
        , Element.centerY
        , Element.Background.color (Element.rgb255 150 150 250)
        , Element.width (Element.px 150)
        , Element.height (Element.px 150)
        ]
        (Element.el
            -- these two centers the Element.text in div
            [ Element.centerX, Element.centerY ]
            (Element.text "CENTERED")
        )
```

### Code Example: Only elm-ui

```elm
import Element exposing (Element)
import Element.Background as Background
import Element.Font as Font

box : Element a
box =
    Element.el
        [ Element.centerX
        , Element.centerY
        , Background.color (Element.rgb255 150 150 250)
        , Font.size 16
        ]
        (Element.text "Hello")
```

## Html Module Imports

When using `elm/html`, follow these import patterns:

### Standard Imports

```elm
import Html exposing (Html)
import Html.Attributes as Attr
```

**Guidelines:**

-   Use `import Html exposing (Html)` to expose only the Html type
-   Use `import Html.Attributes as Attr` with the `Attr` alias
-   This allows clear usage: `Html.div`, `Html.text`, `Attr.class`, `Attr.id`

### Code Example

```elm
import Html exposing (Html)
import Html.Attributes as Attr

myDiv : Html msg
myDiv =
    Html.div
        [ Attr.class "container"
        , Attr.id "main-content"
        ]
        [ Html.text "Hello, World!" ]
```

## General Import Guidelines

**Import patterns:**

-   ✅ `import Html exposing (Html)` (expose only the type)
-   ✅ `import Element exposing (Element)` (expose only the type)
-   ✅ `import Html.Attributes as Attr` (with alias)
-   ✅ `import Element.Background as Background` (alias OK if only elm-ui)
-   ✅ `import Element.Background` (fully qualified when mixing with Html)

**Decision rule:**

-   **Only elm-ui modules**: Aliases are acceptable and can improve readability
-   **Mixed elm-ui + Html**: Use fully qualified names to avoid confusion

**Benefits:**

-   Clear namespace separation
-   Easy to identify where functions come from
-   Prevents naming conflicts
-   Better code readability
-   Type-only exposing keeps the namespace clean while allowing concise type annotations

